  <p>
   <font face="palatino">
    <a href="definitions/ecws_def.html" onclick="window.open('definitions/ecws_def.html','defwindow_blank','menubar=1,resizable=1,width=350,height=250,left=00,top=y00,screenX=00,screenY=00'); return false">
     <color="blue">
      <b>
       East coast winter storms
      </b>
     </color="blue">
    </a>
    have a major impact on coastal communities in New York.  These storms cause more damage than hurricanes due to their frequency.  This web site is designed to provide seasonal forecasts and climatological data on east coast winter storms that can be used by managers and other coastal audiences to better prepare for and respond to these events.  The site includes information on the following:
   </font>
  </p>
 </body>
</html>
<p>
 <center>
  <table border="0" cellpadding="10" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
   <font size="-1">
    <!-- Leftmost Column: Enter Front Page Text Here  -->
    <tr>
     <td align="LEFT" valign="center" width="35%">
      <ul>
       <li>
        <b>
         Historic Analogue Storm:
        </b>
        This link provides the storm track and changes in the associated storm surge (as time series plots at selected stations) for historically significant winter storms. An option also allows the user to compare a current forecasted storm to all historical storms and displays the track and surges associated with the most similar historical storm.
       </li>
      </ul>
     </td>
     <!-- Second Column: Images & Links To Other Pages Within This Site  -->
     <td align="CENTER" valign="center" width="15%">
      <a href="stormtrack.html">
       <img border="0" src="images/stormtrack.jpg"/>
       <br/>
       <font size="+0">
        <b>
         Analogue Storm Tracks
        </b>
       </font>
      </a>
     </td>
     <!-- Third Column: Images & Links To Other Pages Within This Site  -->
     <td align="LEFT" valign="top" width="35%">
      <ul>
       <li>
        <b>
         Storm Climatology:
        </b>
        Climatology is the study of weather conditions over an extended period of time.  This link provides information on the number of storms in a given year (dating back to 1950 when available) and the associated storm surges based on measurements made at several NOAA tide gauge stations in the area.
       </li>
      </ul>
     </td>
     <!-- Rightmost Column: Images & Links To Other Pages Within This Site  -->
     <td align="LEFT" valign="center" width="15%">
      <a href="ECWS_graphs.html">
       <img alt="Storm  Climatology" border="0" src="images/stormclimo.jpg"/>
       <br/>
       <font size="+0">
        <b>
         Storm Climatology
        </b>
       </font>
      </a>
     </td>
    </tr>
    <!-- Leftmost Column: Enter Front Page Text Here  -->
    <tr>
     <td align="LEFT" valign="center">
      <ul>
       <li>
        <b>
         Seasonal Storm Outlook:
        </b>
        Forecasts of winter storm and surge activity for the upcoming (current) winter storm season (October to April).
       </li>
      </ul>
     </td>
     <!-- Second Column: Images & Links To Other Pages Within This Site  -->
     <td align="LEFT" valign="center">
      <a href="strong_forecast.html">
       <img border="0" src="images/stormfreq.jpg"/>
       <br/>
       <font size="+0">
        <b>
         Seasonal Storm Outlook
        </b>
       </font>
      </a>
     </td>
    </tr>
   </font>
  </table>
 </center>
</p>
<!-- Third Column: Images & Links To Other Pages Within This Site  -->
<td align="LEFT" valign="center">
 <ul>
  <li>
   <b>
    Current Observations:
   </b>
   Sites providing real time meteorological and oceanographic data and forecasts related to storms and waterlevels for New York waters.
  </li>
 </ul>
</td>
